Create a multi-class [confusion matrix](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/plot_confusion_matrix.html) in one line:
    
    
    import wandb
    
    cm = wandb.plot.confusion_matrix(
        y_true=ground_truth, preds=predictions, class_names=class_names
    )
    
    with wandb.init() as run:
        run.log({"conf_mat": cm})
    

You can log this wherever your code has access to:

  * A model’s predicted labels on a set of examples (`preds`) or the normalized probability scores (`probs`). The probabilities must have the shape (number of examples, number of classes). You can supply either probabilities or predictions but not both.
  * The corresponding ground truth labels for those examples (`y_true`).
  * A full list of the labels or class names as strings in `class_names`. For example, `class_names=["cat", "dog", "bird"]`, if index 0 is `cat`, 1 is `dog`, 2 is `bird`.



![Confusion matrix](https://mintcdn.com/wb-21fd5541/88iR80mZ8tuFCZUU/images/experiments/confusion_matrix.png?fit=max&auto=format&n=88iR80mZ8tuFCZUU&q=85&s=eb980135fce1c4b0960f03cef572420a)

For more information, see the [Confusion Matrix: Usage and Examples](https://wandb.ai/wandb/plots/reports/Confusion-Matrix--VmlldzozMDg1NTM) report.[Run the code](https://colab.research.google.com/github/wandb/examples/blob/master/colabs/wandb-log/Log_a_Confusion_Matrix_with_W%26B.ipynb)

